          "text": "<teammate-message teammate_id=\"core-reviewer\" color=\"blue\" summary=\"Complete review findings for Task #1 - core module test quality\">\n## Task #1 Review: Test Quality and RFC Compliance for Core Modules\n\nAll four test files reviewed. Every test suite passes: ecard-test.el (113/113), ecard-compat-test.el (142/142), ecard-tools-test.el (355/355), ecard-org-test.el (176/176).\n\n---\n\n### 1. ecard-test.el (113 tests, tests for ecard.el)\n\n**GOOD: Comprehensive RFC 6350 property coverage**\nThe test suite covers all major RFC 6350 property types including structured values (N, ADR, ORG, GENDER), text-list values (CATEGORIES, NICKNAME), cardinality constraints (*1 properties), KIND/MEMBER validation, PREF parameter validation (1-100), escaping rules, and UTF-8 line folding. This is thorough RFC compliance testing.\n\n**GOOD: Folding test is RFC-correct (lines 57-68, 195-210)**\nThe test data places the fold between \"Seventy\" and \"Five\" where the leading space on the continuation line is the fold continuation character. Per RFC 6350 Section 3.2, CRLF+SP is removed, correctly producing \"SeventyFive Octets\". The comment at line 202 (\"no space\") is accurate.\n\n**GOOD: Round-trip fidelity tests**\nTests verify parse-serialize round-trips preserve data integrity. The `ecard-round-trip-test` (line 263) and `ecard-round-trip-fidelity-test` (line 273) check structural equivalence rather than byte-identical strings, which is correct since whitespace normalization is expected.\n\n**GOOD: Multi-record parsing tests (lines 303-404)**\nTests handle multiple vCards in a single stream, mixed with complex vCards, and malformed separators between records.\n\n**GOOD: Extended property escaping tests (lines 1555-1600)**\nTests verify that backslash, comma, semicolon, and combined escaping all work correctly in X-* properties per RFC 6350 Section 3.4.\n\n**ISSUE (minor): EIEIO accessor usage throughout**\nTests use `oref` at lines 176, 225-226, 231-232, 442, 1339-1341, 1374-1375, 1398-1399, 1424, 1426, 1434, 1444-1445, 1455, 1564, 1572, 1580, 1588, 1644. The source code migrated from EIEIO `defclass` to `cl-defstruct`. While `oref`/`oset` happen to work on `cl-defstruct` objects in modern Emacs (EIEIO provides fallback support), using the generated accessor functions (`ecard-property-parameters`, `ecard-property-value`, `ecard-property-group`, `ecard-extended`) would be more idiomatic and explicit. This creates an implicit dependency on EIEIO being loaded.\n\n**ISSUE (minor): Missing negative folding test**\nThe folding test verifies correct unfolding but doesn't test that folding output breaks at exactly 75 octets. A test asserting `(= (length (encode-coding-string line 'utf-8)) 75)` for each folded line would verify the 75-octet boundary per RFC 6350 Section 3.2.\n\n**GOOD: Error handling tests**\nTests verify `ecard-parse-error` and `ecard-validation-error` for malformed input, missing VERSION, wrong VERSION, and missing FN.\n\n**GOOD: Gap analysis documentation (lines 1848-1975)**\nThe embedded gap analysis identifying untested areas is useful for future test development.\n\n---\n\n### 2. ecard-compat-test.el (142 tests, tests for ecard-compat.el)\n\n**GOOD: Version detection tests (lines 19-35)**\nTests correctly identify vCard 2.1, 3.0, 4.0, and unknown versions.\n\n**GOOD: Encoding tests (lines 37-80)**\nTests cover BASE64 and QUOTED-PRINTABLE decoding for vCard 2.1, including multiline QUOTED-PRINTABLE with soft line breaks — a common real-world scenario.\n\n**GOOD: vCard 2.1 parameter conversion (lines 83-100)**\nTests verify that legacy 2.1 parameter syntax (e.g., `TEL;HOME;VOICE`) is correctly converted to 4.0 syntax (`TYPE=home,voice`).\n\n**GOOD: Multi-vCard parsing (lines 254-290)**\nTests handle multiple vCards in a single file/buffer, including mixed 2.1/3.0 versions.\n\n**GOOD: Comprehensive serialization tests (lines 520-800+)**\nTests cover serializing ecard objects back to vCard 3.0 format including TEL parameters, email addresses, organizations, photos, and addresses.\n\n**ISSUE (minor): EIEIO accessor usage throughout**\nUses `slot-value` at lines 116, 125, 139, 193, 230, 392 and `oref` at lines 118-119, 127, 141, 195, 232-233, and `oset` at lines 559, 639, 650, 746, 766. Same concern as ecard-test.el — these work but are not idiomatic for `cl-defstruct`. Should use the generated accessor functions and `setf` with accessors instead of `oset`.\n\n**GOOD: Regression tests (lines 900+)**\nContains tests for specific bugs that were found and fixed, preventing regressions.\n\n**GOOD: Round-trip tests (lines 807-870)**\nTests convert 2.1→4.0 and 3.0→4.0 and verify key properties survive the conversion. This is important for the compatibility layer.\n\n**SUGGESTION (minor): Add vCard 2.1 line encoding test**\nvCard 2.1 uses `=\\r\\n` soft line breaks for QUOTED-PRINTABLE continuation rather than RFC 6350's CRLF+SP folding. While the QUOTED-PRINTABLE decoding is tested, a test specifically verifying that QUOTED-PRINTABLE properties spanning multiple lines with `=\\r\\n` are correctly rejoined would document this distinction.\n\n---\n\n### 3. ecard-tools-test.el (355 tests, tests for ecard-tools.el and ecard-tools-adapter.el)\n\n**GOOD: Comprehensive adapter layer coverage**\nThe adapter layer between `ecard` cl-defstruct objects and the `ecard-tools-vcard` interface is thoroughly tested. Tests cover: create adapter (from raw text, from keywords, with all field types), copy adapter (basic, independence/deep copy), all property accessors (getters and setters for fn, uid, n, org, title, note, bday, url, categories, email, tel, adr, photo, version, valid-p, modified-p, file-path, raw, properties), and predicates (vcard-p, email-p, tel-p, adr-p).\n\n**GOOD: File I/O tests with proper cleanup (lines 609-832)**\nTests use `make-temp-file`, `unwind-protect`, and `delete-directory` for proper test isolation. Tests cover: read-file (success, nonexistent, multi-entry), read-directory (basic, empty, recursive, stats), write-file (basic, creates directory, backup, no-backup), write-multiple (basic, creates dir, custom filename).\n\n**GOOD: Version conversion tests (lines 1779-1813)**\nTests for v3→v4 and v4→v3 conversion cover basic conversion, passthrough of already-correct version, line unfolding during conversion, and TYPE parameter case conversion.\n\n**GOOD: Mock-based API testing (lines 1418-1540)**\nHTTP POST and OpenAI API calls are properly mocked using `cl-letf` to override function definitions. This ensures tests don't make real network calls while verifying the integration logic.\n\n**GOOD: Duplicate detection tests (lines 1179-1510)**\nTests cover simple duplicate detection, ML-based similarity detection, AI-based merge decisions (with mocked API), prompt formatting, and response parsing. The tests correctly verify both \"duplicates found\" and \"no duplicates\" paths.\n\n**GOOD: Integration workflow tests (lines 1730-1773)**\nTests verify multi-step workflows like read→write→read roundtrip and split→read→validate pipeline.\n\n**ISSUE (moderate): Some tests verify only \"no error\" rather than outcomes**\nSeveral tests only verify that functions execute without error rather than checking actual results. For example:\n- `ecard-tools-test-add-uids` (line 893): Only verifies files are still readable after add-uids, not that UIDs were actually added\n- `ecard-tools-test-cleanup-directory` (line 965): Verifies good card still exists but doesn't verify junk card was moved to trash\n- `ecard-tools-test-remove-notes-basic` (line 1062): Only verifies file still readable, not that notes were removed\n\nThese tests document that the function runs without error but don't verify the core behavior. The test comments explain this is because \"file-path metadata is not persisted by the adapter layer, so the write-back is a no-op\" — this is an architectural limitation worth noting.\n\n**ISSUE (minor): Chunk file tests are weak (lines 918-